<TITLE> Cold snap in Srimangal hits the poor </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Moulvibazar, February 15 (bdnews24.com)Meteorologists recorded 5.2 degrees Celsius in temperature in Srimangal Friday, the country's lowest so far this winter. Goutam Acharya, senior meteorologist of Srimangal weather monitoring office, told bdnews24.com that the temperature was recorded at 9am. The second lowest temperature so far, 5.6 degrees Celsius, was recorded by the same monitoring office on Feb 3. Goutam said cold winds blowing in from the north are making the conditions even more dangerous to vulnerable groups such as the elderly, poor or infirm. According to the weather office, the lowest temperature ever recorded in Bangladesh was at Srimangal in 1968. The temperature then dipped to 2.8 degrees Celsius. bdnews24.com Srimangal correspondent Kamrul Ambia said tea-garden workers and daily-wage earners have been among the worst-affected by the cold snap. Upazila Nirbahi Officer Md Saiful Islam said they had received some blankets and warm clothes from the chief adviser's relief fund to distribute to the poor. Bangladesh Red Crescent Society has also distributed blankets and clothes to local people. bdnews2
